│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation in foldSelectIntoOp moves a      │
│ floating-point binary operation (FMul/FAdd/etc.) from being only evaluated on │
│ one arm of a select to being evaluated after the select with a select feeding │
│ one operand and the other operand replaced by the operation’s identity        │
│ constant. Under fast-math flags like nnan and ninf, floating-point operations │
│ can become poison if they would otherwise produce NaN or Infinity. In the     │
│ original IR, the FP op is only executed on the true arm; if the condition is  │
│ false, the op is not evaluated, so any potential poison from the FP op does   │
│ not manifest. The transformation, however, makes the FP op always executed    │
│ and thus may introduce poison on paths where select would have avoided        │
│ it.\n\nAlive2 shows precisely this: for x = +inf and FMul with ninf, the      │
│ original program chooses the false arm (%x) and returns +inf (no poison),     │
│ while the transformed program computes x * 1.0 with ninf, which is considered │
│ poison, making the target more poisonous than the source.\n\n2. Analyzing     │
│ opt's Log:\nThe first transformation occurs in                                │
│ InstCombinerImpl::foldSelectIntoOp, rewriting:\n  select nnan i1 %cond, (fmul │
│ nnan ninf nsz %x, %x), %x\ninto:\n  %scaled.x = select nnan i1 %cond, %x,     │
│ 1.0\n  %res = fmul nnan ninf nsz %x, %scaled.x\nThis is the exact             │
│ foldSelectIntoOp pattern: replace one operand with identity C and use a       │
│ select for the other operand. The log shows no additional safety checks       │
│ around NoInfs beyond an existing NaN check.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn    │
│ foldSelectIntoOp, there is a check to avoid folding if the false value might  │
│ be a NaN when the select and the FP op have fast-math flags (nnan), using     │
│ computeKnownFPClass(..., fcNan). However, there is no similar check for       │
│ infinities when ninf is present. As a result, the fold can introduce          │
│ immediate poison by evaluating the FP op with an operand that may be infinite │
│ (FalseVal) combined with the identity, producing an infinity result and       │
│ violating NoInfs. The original program would not evaluate that op on the      │
│ false path, so this is a miscompile.\n\nWe must add a guard: if the select is │
│ an FPMathOperator and the resulting FP op will carry NoInfs, ensure the false │
│ value cannot be infinity under the given FMF and context. If it might be      │
│ infinity, do not perform the folding.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:  │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp\n- Function:            │
│ InstCombinerImpl::foldSelectIntoOp\n- Location: Immediately after the         │
│ existing NaN guard (lines ~555-557) and before creating the NewSel and        │
│ BO.\n\nEdit:\nInsert an additional check mirroring the NaN check, but for     │
│ infinity when NoInfs is set. Specifically:\n\nLines 555-557 (context existing │
│ NaN check):\n  if (isa<FPMathOperator>(&SI) &&\n                              │
│ !computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FMF, fcNan, &SI).isKnownNeverNaN())\n          │
│ return nullptr;\n\nLines 558-563 (new code to add):\n  // If the false value  │
│ may be infinity and the FP operation has 'no-infs',\n  // then moving the     │
│ operation after the select could introduce poison on the\n  // false path     │
│ (e.g., 'fmul ninf x, 1.0' when x is +inf). Avoid the folding.\n  if           │
│ (isa<FPMathOperator>(&SI) && FMF.noInfs()) {\n    if                          │
│ (!computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FMF, fcInf, &SI).isKnownNeverInf())\n         │
│ return nullptr;\n  }\n\nThis uses the same computeKnownFPClass utility to     │
│ conservatively determine whether FalseVal could be an infinity under the      │
│ given FMF and context. If it could, we bail out and do not perform the        │
