│ Alive2 shows precisely this: for x = +inf and FMul with ninf, the original    │
│ program chooses the false arm (%x) and returns +inf (no poison), while the    │
│ transformed program computes x * 1.0 with ninf, which is considered poison,   │
│ making the target more poisonous than the source.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The first transformation occurs in InstCombinerImpl::foldSelectIntoOp,        │
│ rewriting:                                                                    │
│   select nnan i1 %cond, (fmul nnan ninf nsz %x, %x), %x                       │
│ into:                                                                         │
│   %scaled.x = select nnan i1 %cond, %x, 1.0                                   │
│   %res = fmul nnan ninf nsz %x, %scaled.x                                     │
│ This is the exact foldSelectIntoOp pattern: replace one operand with identity │
│ C and use a select for the other operand. The log shows no additional safety  │
│ checks around NoInfs beyond an existing NaN check.                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In foldSelectIntoOp, there is a check to avoid folding if the false value     │
│ might be a NaN when the select and the FP op have fast-math flags (nnan),     │
│ using computeKnownFPClass(..., fcNan). However, there is no similar check for │
│ infinities when ninf is present. As a result, the fold can introduce          │
│ immediate poison by evaluating the FP op with an operand that may be infinite │
│ (FalseVal) combined with the identity, producing an infinity result and       │
│ violating NoInfs. The original program would not evaluate that op on the      │
│ false path, so this is a miscompile.                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ We must add a guard: if the select is an FPMathOperator and the resulting FP  │
│ op will carry NoInfs, ensure the false value cannot be infinity under the     │
│ given FMF and context. If it might be infinity, do not perform the folding.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                 │
│ - Function: InstCombinerImpl::foldSelectIntoOp                                │
│ - Location: Immediately after the existing NaN guard (lines ~555-557) and     │
│ before creating the NewSel and BO.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit:                                                                         │
│ Insert an additional check mirroring the NaN check, but for infinity when     │
│ NoInfs is set. Specifically:                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Lines 555-557 (context existing NaN check):                                   │
│   if (isa<FPMathOperator>(&SI) &&                                             │
│       !computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FMF, fcNan, &SI).isKnownNeverNaN())      │
│     return nullptr;                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Lines 558-563 (new code to add):                                              │
│   // If the false value may be infinity and the FP operation has 'no-infs',   │
│   // then moving the operation after the select could introduce poison on the │
│   // false path (e.g., 'fmul ninf x, 1.0' when x is +inf). Avoid the folding. │
│   if (isa<FPMathOperator>(&SI) && FMF.noInfs()) {                             │
│     if (!computeKnownFPClass(FalseVal, FMF, fcInf, &SI).isKnownNeverInf())    │
│       return nullptr;                                                         │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This uses the same computeKnownFPClass utility to conservatively determine    │
│ whether FalseVal could be an infinity under the given FMF and context. If it  │
│ could, we bail out and do not perform the transformation.                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By adding a guard for NoInfs analogous to the existing NoNaNs guard, we       │
│ prevent foldSelectIntoOp from introducing poison by making an FP operation    │
│ execute unconditionally when the false arm could be infinite. This fixes the  │
│ miscompile demonstrated in the reproducer: the transform will now be rejected │
│ when %x may be +inf, preserving the original program’s poison semantics and   │
│ satisfying Alive2.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
